SIMPLE: sculpture
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sculpture
<hw>Sculp"ture</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sculptura</ets>: cf. F. <ets>sculpture</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The art of carving, cutting, or hewing wood, stone, metal, etc.,
into statues, ornaments, etc., or into figures, as of men, or other
things; hence, the art of producing figures and groups, whether in
plastic or hard materials.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Carved work modeled of, or cut upon, wood, stone,
metal, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There, too, in living <qex>sculpture</qex>, might be seen⟦br⟧
The mad affection of the Cretan queen.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sculpture</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sculpture
<hw>Sculp"ture</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Sculptured</conjf>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sculpturing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To form with the chisel on,
in, or from, wood, stone, or metal; to carve; to engrave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sculptured tortoise</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a
common North American wood tortoise (<spn>Glyptemys insculpta</spn>).
The shell is marked with strong grooving and ridges which resemble
sculptured figures.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sculpturesque</ent>⟦br⟧
